from pymilvus import MilvusClient

    uri=CLUSTER_ENDPOINT, # Cluster endpoint obtained from the console

On Zilliz Cloud, you need to store your vector embeddings in collections. All vector embeddings stored in a collection share the same dimensionality and distance metric for measuring similarity.
The following code snippet creates a collection with

res = client.create_collection(
    collection_name="medium_articles_2020",
    dimension=768,
    metric_type="COSINE"
)

# Output
The collection generated in the above code contains only two fields:
Enabling this feature by setting this to
means that the primary key of the collection automatically increments. There is no requirement to manually provide primary keys when inserting data.
Enabling this feature by setting this to
will be treated as dynamic fields.  This allows you to include additional fields in the data during the insertion process.
Alternatively, you have the option to create a collection by providing detailed definitions for its schema and index parameters.

from pymilvus import DataType

# 1. Create the schema
schema = client.create_schema(
    enable_dynamic_field=True
)

# add the primary key
schema.add_field("id", DataType.INT64, is_primary=True, auto_id=True)

# add the vector field
schema.add_field("vector", DataType.FLOAT_VECTOR, dimension=768)

# add other scalar fields
schema.add_field("title", DataType.VARCHAR, max_length=512)
schema.add_field("link", DataType.VARCHAR, max_length=512),
schema.add_field("reading_time", DataType.INT64),
schema.add_field("publication", DataType.VARCHAR, max_length=512),

# 2. Set index parameters
index_params = client.prepare_index_params()

# Add an index on the vector field.
index_params.add_index(
    field_name="vector",
    metric_type="COSINE",
    index_type="AUTOINDEX"
)

# You can add indices on scalar fields too.
index_params.add_index(
    field_name="title",

"
)

# 3. Create collection
res = client.create_collection(
    collection_name="medium_articles_2020",
    schema=schema,
    index_params=index_params
)

# Output
As demonstrated in the code above, you have the flexibility to define various aspects of the collection during its creation, including its schema and index parameters.
The schema defines the structure of a collection. Within a schema, you have the option to enable or disable
, add pre-defined fields, and set attributes for each field. For a detailed explanation of the schema, refer to

as the index type and choose

The subsequent code snippets will use the collection with the manually defined schema and index parameters.

The data to insert does not contain the primary key
The data to insert is organized into a list of dictionaries, where each dictionary represents a data record, termed as an entity.
Each dictionary contains the keys corresponding to both pre-defined and dynamic fields.
For the sake of the search later, you can add more records to the collection.
You can conduct similarity searches based on one or more vector embeddings.
Search with a single vector embedding.
variable is a list containing a sub-list of floats. The sub-list represents a vector-embedding of 768 dimensions.
The output is a list containing a sub-list of three dictionaries, representing the returned entities with their IDs and distances.
You can also include multiple vector-embeddings in the
variable to conduct a bulk similarity search.
The output should be a list of two sub-lists, each of which contains three dictionaries, representing the returned entities with their IDs and distances.
Search with filter expressions using fields defined in the schema.
You can also enhance the search result by including a filter and specifying certain output fields in the search request.
The output should be a list containing a sub-list of three dictionaries, each representing a searched entity with its ID, distance, and the specified output fields.
Search with filter expressions using dynamic fields.
